node.text: Our Adaptable, Deployable Entry Placement Technology, or ADEPT, is a next-generation heat shield design for delivering jumbo-size payloads to planetary surfaces. Made of 3D woven carbon fabric, it can open like an umbrella and withstands temperatures greater than 3,000 degrees Fahrenheit. In this video, its new seamless “spiderweave” knit is put to the test at our facility that simulates the intense heating spacecraft experience during atmospheric entry.

node.text:
Vice President Kamala Harris recently spoke with astronauts Dr. Shannon Walker and Dr. Kate Rubins aboard the International Space Station and got to meet Honey, one of our Astrobee robots!
 
The cube-shaped robots will help astronauts reduce time they spend on routine duties, leaving them to focus more on the things that only humans can do in space. Robots like Astrobee will play a significant part in our mission to return to the Moon under the Artemis program by helping maintain spacecraft when astronauts are not aboard. 
 
The vice president also learned about our Micro-16 biology experiment, which uses worms to explore the cause of muscle weakening that astronauts can experience in microgravity. The results could support new therapies to combat the effects of age-related muscle loss on Earth.

Learn more about Astrobee: https://www.nasa.gov/astrobee

Learn more about Micro-16: https://go.nasa.gov/3reoyGQ
 
Video credit: NASA
#nasa #amesresearchcenter #space #robot #astrobee #astronaut #spacestation #artemis

node.title: Vice President Harris Calls NASA Astronauts

node.text: Our Adaptable, Deployable Entry Placement Technology, or ADEPT, is a next-generation heat shield design for delivering jumbo-size payloads to planetary surfaces. Made of 3D woven carbon fabric, it can open like an umbrella and withstands temperatures greater than 3,000 degrees Fahrenheit. In this video, its new seamless “spiderweave” knit is put to the test at our facility that simulates the intense heating spacecraft experience during atmospheric entry.

The City by the Bay is just north of our Silicon Valley center, and with #NationalAviationDay on the horizon we are reminiscing over some scenic flights we have done around San Francisco’s iconic sights. Do you recognize them?

node.text:
This robot has got you covered.
 
Our #Astrobee Bumble detected an anomaly aboard the International Space Station (@iss) — part of a simulation to test the robot’s response to a potentially dangerous situation. 
 
The exercise marked the end of the first phase of testing for the Integrated System for Autonomous and Adaptive Caretaking system, or ISAAC, software. The technology is designed to enable autonomous operations of a spacecraft’s systems including both general maintenance and responding to crises — even when no crew is around. It could be vital for future deep space exploration and managing Gateway, the Artemis (@NASAArtemis) program’s lunar outpost. 
 
Image credit: NASA 
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/2XnHIAl

We are celebrating our stellar space telescopes with groovy new posters! 

You can choose our Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite, or TESS, which has been hunting the skies since 2018 and monitoring more than 200,000 pre-selected stars in that time. Or you can commemorate the Kepler space telescope, which discovered more than 2,600 planets outside our solar system after nine years in deep space!

node.text:
Our planetary neighbor is less than hospitable...

But despite it’s toxic and hellish environment, we launched probes to Venus #OTD in 1978. The Venus Pioneer 2 consisted of the main spacecraft, a large probe, and three identical small probes — all designed to collect data as they descended toward the surface of the planet. Two of the probes survived the hard impact with the surface, and one continued transmitting data for 67 minutes before being crushed by the atmosphere. 

This artwork by Rick Guidice depicts the Pioneer Venus Orbiter and Pioneer Venus Multiprobe. 

Image credit: NASA/Rick Guidice 
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/2VwRTl8 

#nasa #AmesResearchCenter #space #spacecraft #pioneer #SolarSystem #SpaceArt #Venus

node.text:
Coming soon to an orbit near the Moon. 🌔 

The Cislunar Autonomous Positioning System Technology Operations and Navigation Experiment, or CAPSTONE, #CubeSat will fly in cislunar space – the orbital area near and around the Moon — after it launches from New Zealand later this year. In doing so, CAPSTONE will serve as a pathfinder for a future Moon-orbiting outpost in NASA’s Artemis program (@NASAArtemis) known as Gateway (@NASA_Gateway).

In this photo, the 16 square-shaped elements on the surface of CAPSTONE's flat plate are low-profile antennas, called patch antennas. The red structures are handling fixtures that will be removed from the spacecraft prior to testing. 

Image credit: Tyvak Nano-Satellite Systems, Inc. 
Learn more:  https://go.nasa.gov/3Cpm1Q3

#Artemis #NasaGateway #AmesResearchCenter #nasa #space #Satellite #nasakennedy

node.text:
Happy birthday to the first man on the Moon, Neil Armstrong!

Before becoming commander of the Apollo 11 mission, Armstrong was an engineer and a project test pilot. He is also the namesake of NASA's Armstrong Flight Research Center (@NASAArmstrong) in California, and we are celebrating his legacy on what would be his 91st birthday.

In this photograph, Armstrong is seen in the cockpit of the Ames Bell X-14 aircraft during a visit to our Silicon Valley center in 1964. 

Image credit: NASA/Lee Jones
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/3fSFgbt

#NASA #AmesResearchCenter #Moon #NeilArmstrong #nasaArmstrong

node.text:
How many meteors can you count? ☄️ 

As many as 100 can be seen streaking across the night sky every hour during the Perseid meteor shower. The bits of broken asteroids and leftover comet particles disintegrate in a blaze of glory as they collide with Earth’s atmosphere. 

Though the Perseids are visible now and last several weeks, peak viewing this year falls on Aug. 11. This long-exposure photo from 2004 captures 51 Perseid meteors in one composite image. Did you spot them all?

Image credit: Fred Bruenjes 
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/3xpoK8G 

#Meteors #MeteorShower #Perseids #nasa #AmesResearchCenter #Astronomy #Space

node.text:
Aircraft assemble! ✈️🚁🔥

As climate change impacts extreme weather events, there may be an increasing need for tools like our Scalable Traffic Management for Emergency Response Operations project, or STEReO, which aims to manage and track personnel in the sky and on the ground to improve emergency response. 

We tested the software's abilitiy to coordinate piloted and uncrewed aircraft during flight demonstrations in Northern California, and continue to develop it in collaboration with NASA's Langley Research Center (@nasa_langley) and NASA's Glenn Research Center (@nasaglenn).

Image credit: NASA/Joel Kowsky 
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/3yqoo2Q

We're sitting ringside!

Saturn is in opposition, forming a straight line with us and the Sun, and making its closest approach to Earth for the year. 🪐 🌎 ☀️ 

It's prime time to observe the ringed giant, and learn about Pioneer 11 — the first spacecraft to get close to the sixth planet from the Sun.

Image credit: NASA/JPL/Space Science Institute
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/3ygQY6S

#Saturn #Pioneer11 #Planet #nasa #AmesResearchCenter #SolarSystem

node.text:
Is this a cosmic bread maker? Or is it the first long-duration biology experiment headed for deep space?

Our BioSentinel #CubeSat will carry yeast cells out of low-Earth orbit and beyond the Moon. Identical cells will be studied here on Earth and on the International Space Station (@iss) to determine the effect of space radiation on living organisms.

Human cells and yeast cells share similar biological mechanisms, so BioSentinel's data could help us understand how astronauts are impacted during deep space exploration — critical insight as we work to establish long-term human exploration of the Moon under Artemis (@NASAArtemis) and prepare for human exploration on Mars.

Image credit: NASA
Learn more: go.nasa.gov/3rHRE2n

#nasa #Artemis #AmesResearchCenter #Satellite #BioSentinel #NASAJohnson #Space
